full_text: It is unlikely that our application could be used as a countermeasure against the potential Russian use of a weapon of mass destruction in time for the July summit. 12/14

The main thing is that the Kyiv Security Compact should not be used to claim Ukraine is uncertain about NATO membership, so as not to distract attention from the prospects of membership itself. The Kyiv Security Compact and Ukraine‚Äôs NATO aspirations are not contradictory. 11/14
As soon as Sweden and Finland indicated their willingness to become NATO members, they almost immediately signed security agreements with Britain. It was a clear message. 10/14

The Kyiv Security Compact is an additional, temporary mechanism on the way to NATO membership. Member status is a long-term prospect. Questions about the content of the Kyiv Security Compact and the countries willing to sign onto it. 9/14

Ukraine recorded its desire to join back in the 2000s (let us recall the Letter of the Three when we started an intensified dialogue), which is part of the procedure, and when we established it in our Constitution. 8/14

Our application was an important political act to demonstrate the unchanging nature of our position both domestically and internationally. Procedurally, the application can be either oral or written. The Poles did not write letters to join NATO, but the Swedes did. 7/14

If we look at the essence of what was included in MAPs and what is contained in our annual National Program, these are almost identical documents. The annual National Program serves as a supporting document for Ukrainian NATO membership. 6/14
The MAP is an auxiliary document meant to help better implement the reforms of the countries seeking membership. Its essence lies in advice and assistance, not extortion. 5/14

The foundational documents of the North Atlantic Treaty from 1949 agreement provide a simple procedure: countries express their wish to join NATO, and then member states invite it by voting unanimously. 4/14

The Treaty states clearly that a candidate country must contribute to transatlantic security. Accordingly, when there are active hostilities, disputes arise: is the candidate country protecting Europe, or will it bring additional problems? 3/14
It is hardly possible for Ukraine to join NATO during active military operations. The reason is not limited by mere technicalities, but by the North Atlantic Treaty itself. 2/14
